Here we see that the mean and the median of Insulin column are very different from each other, so we cannot use mean to replace 0 value.¶

Most of the values are between 0 and 200. So we can use 100 which is the range of the two values .¶

We can replace the 0 value with the value 100.

In [26]:
inp_data['Insulin'].replace(0,100,inplace=True)
In [27]:
inp_data[inp_data['Insulin'] == 0]
Out[27]:
Pregnancies Glucose BloodPressure SkinThickness Insulin BMI DiabetesPedigreeFunction Age Outcome

since both mean and the median of BMI column are almost similar, we can replace 0 with mean¶

In [28]:
inp_data['BMI'].replace(0,inp_data['BMI'].mean(),inplace=True)
In [29]:
inp_data[inp_data['BMI']==0]

From the above histogram ploted for Outcome=0 and 1, we infer that,¶

    People with Glucose level less than 80 are less prone to diabetes.
    People with glucose range 150 to 200 are more prone to diabetes.
    The people with insulin value 100 has a partial chance of getting diabetes.But we also see that people with insulin value 100 are more in the non-diabeteic group.
    People with BMI range of 35 has a greater possiblity of getting diabetets.
    Peoplw with BMI less than 22 are less prone to diabetes
